<<#
This is the golden test fixture for block parameters: `{Label}(key=value, ...)`
and `{{Label}}(key=value, ...)`. It exercises version/segment/postscript
parameter lists, variable substitution in parameter values, and the
shell-word-style value scanner (adjacent quoted/unquoted segments, backslash
escaping, a value containing the other quote character, a comma, and a
closing parenthesis). This comment block never appears in the output.
#>>

={want preview}=false

Params Example
1970-02-01

{{ Version 1 }}(color=blue, icon=star)

{Verse}(preview-lines=8)
A single segment to keep this fixture minimal.

====

====

{My Postscript Label}(preview=${want preview})
This postscript's preview parameter is expanded from a variable that was
defined above as "false".

----

{Quoting Stress}( tricky-1   = " )' "  , tricky-2=  '(")'    )
This postscript exercises the exact quoting worked example: tricky-1 is the
four characters space, close-paren, single-quote, space; tricky-2 is the
three characters open-paren, double-quote, close-paren.

----

{Shell Escaping}(path=/usr\ local"/bin", note=a\"quote\"here)
This postscript exercises shell-word value scanning: path concatenates an
unquoted run containing a backslash-escaped space with an adjacent
double-quoted segment, decoding to "/usr local/bin"; note uses an unquoted
backslash-escaped double-quote character, decoding to a\"quote\"here.

----

{Malformed Parenthetical} (see below)
A trailing parenthetical that is not a well-formed parameter list is ignored,
exactly as before: this label is just "Malformed Parenthetical" with no params.

====
